**Idea:** Similar to [LC 15. 3Sum](https://leetcode.com/problems/3sum/discuss/339850/Java-or-Two-pointers-or-Time-beats-100-or-Memory-beats-93)
* Sort the array and have 3 pointers: at start, at end of the array and one moving from start + 1 to end - 1
* If sum of numbers at these 3 pointers equals target, then exit with target
* Else if sum < target, it means you need to add more to the sum, so move middle pointer forward
* Else move the end pointer backwards because the sum is too high
* Keep a running minimum difference to find the closest the sum gets to target
>**T/S:** O(n\xB2)/O(n), where n = size(nums)
Arrays.sort uses dual pivot quick sort which takes extra O(n) space
```
public int threeSumClosest(int[] nums, int target) {
	var closest = 0;
	var n = nums.length;
	var minDiff = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
	Arrays.sort(nums);

	for (var i = 0; i < n - 2; i++) {
		var k = n - 1;

		for (var j = i + 1; j < k;) {
			var sum = nums[i] + nums[j] + nums[k];

			if (sum == target)
				return target;
			if (sum < target)
				j++;
			else
				k--;

			var diff = Math.abs(target - sum);
			if (diff < minDiff) {
				minDiff = diff;
				closest = sum;
			}
		}
	}
	return closest;
}
```
