# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Sort the input array nums to enable the two-pointer approach, which helps in efficiently finding the three integers with the closest sum to the target value.

Initialize closestSum and minDiff to large values, as placeholders for the closest sum and minimum difference between sum and target, respectively.

Loop through the array from index 0 to nums.length - 2, as the three-pointer approach requires at least three elements to find a sum.

Inside the loop, set up two pointers, left and right, to the elements immediately after the current element and the last element of the array, respectively.

Use a while loop to continuously move the left and right pointers towards each other until they meet or cross each other.

Calculate the current sum by adding the values at the current element, nums[left], and nums[right].

Calculate the absolute difference between the current sum and the target value, and update minDiff and closestSum if the current difference is smaller than the previous minimum difference.

If the current sum is less than the target, increment the left pointer to consider a larger value.

If the current sum is greater than the target, decrement the right pointer to consider a smaller value.

If the current sum is equal to the target, return it as the closest sum.

After the loop completes, return the closestSum as the final result, which represents the three integers in the array whose sum is closest to the target value. Note that the returned value may be greater or smaller than the target, depending on the input array and target value. Thus, the caller can check the actual difference between the returned sum and the target value if needed. Also, note that this code assumes that the input array nums has at least three elements. If that's not guaranteed, appropriate error handling or input validation should be added. Additionally, the code assumes that the

