The Naive approach of this is used a three pointers and calculate the diff i.e` target-(nums[i] +nums[j] +nums[k])` and check if this is closet to target if yes then `update `else check another index...
In this way We take 0(n^3) time complexity...

Can We do better?? .......
Yes We can

Now suppose if i give u a problem to find the two integer which is closest to target and the array is sorted then how can you solve.......?
**Ans**- Obviously first thing come in my mind is use of two pointer `si,ei` where `si=0` and` ei=n-1`
and it takes 0(n) time complexity;...................Algo(1)

Now we use two pointer approach in given array for every array index element how.? Lets understand..

suppose `target=x`
and i want to find three integers sum which is closest to target..
now we break this into subproblem..
ie. if at` index i` then our new target is find` target-(nums[i)` from `si=i+1` to `ei=n-1` by using Algo(1) we disscused previously 
Initially our global` clsdiff `variable is used update when we find` diff` which is less than our` clsdiff` 
and when we update then we store three integers in `a,b,c`

Here is code...

```
class Solution {
public:
    int threeSumClosest(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
      int a,b,c;
      int clsdiff=INT_MAX;
        int n=nums.size();
        sort(nums.begin(),nums.end());
        for(int i=0;i<n-2;i++){
            int si=i+1;
            int ei=n-1;
            int ntarget=target-nums[i];
            int na=nums[i];
            int nb,nc;
            int diff=INT_MAX;
            while(si<ei){
                if(abs(ntarget-(nums[si]+nums[ei]))<diff){
                    diff=abs(ntarget-(nums[si]+nums[ei]));
                    nb=nums[si];
                    nc=nums[ei];
                }

                if(nums[si]+nums[ei]>ntarget){
                    ei--;
                }
                else{
                    si++;
                }      
            }
            if(diff<clsdiff){
                clsdiff=diff;
                a=na;
                b=nb;
                c=nc;
            }
        } 
        return a+b+c;
    }
};
```
** Time Complextiy-0(n^2) space complexity-0(1)**

