# 1. Brute Force Code
### Approach
Brute Force Approach - Checking for all the possible triplets and then finding the closestSum be analysing the closeness of the currentSum by target. 

### Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n^3)

- Space complexity: O(1)

```
class Solution {
    public int threeSumClosest(int[] nums, int target) {
        int closest = Integer.MAX_VALUE, closestSum = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for(int i=0;i<nums.length-2;i++){
            for(int j=i+1;j<nums.length-1;j++){
                for(int k=j+1;k<nums.length;k++){
                    int sum = nums[i] + nums[j] + nums[k];
                    int close = Math.abs(sum-target);
                    if(close < closest){
                        closest = close;
                        closestSum = sum;
                    }
                }
            }
        }
        return closestSum;
    }
}

// Brute Force Code 
// Time Complexity : O(N^3)
// Space Complexity : O(1)
```

# 2. Optimized 2 Pointers Code
### Approach
- Sort the array and have 3 pointers: at start, at end of the array and one moving from start + 1 to end - 1
- If sum of numbers at these 3 pointers equals target, then exit with target
- Else if sum < target, it means you need to add more to the sum, so move middle pointer forward
- Else move the end pointer backwards because the sum is too high
- Keep a running minimum difference to find the closest the sum gets to target 

### Complexity
- Time complexity: O(nlog(n) + n^2)

- Space complexity: O(1)

```
class Solution {
    public int threeSumClosest(int[] nums, int target) {
        int closest = Integer.MAX_VALUE, closestSum = Integer.MAX_VALUE,i=-1,j=-1,k=-1;
        Arrays.sort(nums);                               // nlog(n)
        for(i=0;i<nums.length-2;i++){                    // O(n)
            j = i+1;
            k = nums.length-1;
            while(j < k){                                // O(n)
                int sum = nums[i] + nums[j] + nums[k];
                if(sum==target){return target;}
                else if(sum<target) {j++;}
                else {k--;}
                // Updating closestSum according to closest
                int close = Math.abs(sum - target);
                if(close<closest){
                    closest = close;
                    closestSum = sum;
                }               
            }
        }
        return closestSum;
    }
}

// Optimized 2 Pointer Code 
// Time Complexity : O(nlog(n) + n^2)
// Space Complexity : O(1)
```

