solutions.content:
# **C++**
## Recursive
Setting the _next_ pointer from the parent node makes for a clean solution. The only thing to worry about is how to handle the far right node of each level, which doesn't have a _next_. This is easy to check for too, just check if the parent node has a _next_ pointer, if it doesn't, then you're at the far right.
```cpp
  void connect(TreeLinkNode *root) {
    if (root && root->left) {
      root->left->next = root->right;
      root->right->next = (root->next) ? root->next->left : nullptr;
      connect(root->left);
      connect(root->right);
    }
  }
```	
## Iterative
Set the _next_ pointer starting from the left of each level, then you can use the _next_ pointer to progress from left to right to complete the level. Once a level is finshed, advance down the left branch and do it again.
```cpp
  void connect(TreeLinkNode *root) {
    for (; root && root->left; root = root->left) {
      for (TreeLinkNode* pos = root; pos; pos = pos->next) {
        pos->left->next = pos->right;
        pos->right->next = (pos->next) ? pos->next->left : nullptr;
      }
    }
  }
```	
# **Java**
## Recursive
```java
    public void connect(TreeLinkNode root) {
      if (null != root && null != root.left) {
        root.left.next = root.right;
        root.right.next = (null != root.next) ? root.next.left : null;
        connect(root.left);
        connect(root.right);
      }
    }
```
## Iterative
```java
    public void connect(TreeLinkNode root) {
      for (; null != root && null != root.left; root = root.left) {
        for (TreeLinkNode pos = root; null != pos; pos = pos.next) {
          pos.left.next = pos.right;
          pos.right.next = (null != pos.next) ? pos.next.left : null;
        }
      }
    }
```
# **C**
Since a c solution would look very much like the c++ solution, I did it slightly differently, but is essentially the same.
```c
struct Node* connect(struct Node* root) {
  if (root) {
    for (struct Node* row_start = root; row_start->left; row_start = row_start->left) {
      struct Node* pos = row_start;
      for (; pos->next; pos = pos->next) {
        pos->left->next = pos->right;
        pos->right->next = pos->next->left;
      }
      pos->left->next = pos->right;
    }
  }
  return root;
}
```

**Note that all solutions abuse the fact that the tree is by definition a perfect binary tree. [Solutions that don't require perfect tree can be found here](https://leetcode.com/problems/populating-next-right-pointers-in-each-node-ii/discuss/163809/C++-iterative-O(1)-space.-Short-and-easy-to-understand-with-detail.-Bonus-2-line-solution-for-fun)**

