solutions.content:
**Explanation:**
* We use a vector for storing the possible numbers, a 2D vector for our result and a temp vector for storing each possible array.
* This problem is similar to Combination Sum II ,except there is a limit in length of the array 'k', and there are no candidate vectors given.
* we use recursive function helper, for finding all the possibilities.
```
    vector<vector<int>> combinationSum3(int k, int n) {
        vector<int> v= {1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,9};
        vector<vector<int>>res;
        vector<int> path;
        if(k==0) return res;
        helper(v,res,path,k,0,n);
        return res;
    }
```
* 	The Helper function consists of the candidates vector(v) , result (res) ,temp vector(path) , length limit (k), iterative index(start) and target sum (target). Notice that we have passed parameters by reference which gives significant advantage in time and space complexities.
* 	we start with 0 as the index in the first iteration. Let's use the given example k=3, target(n) = 7;
* 	we go throught 1 to 9 in an array. we pick the first element and push it in the vector. We decrement our target to target- the picked number and check if the remaining can be achieved by recursion. the start index is incremented because we can only have a max of 1 repetitions of a number. length limit(k) is decremented as we have picked an element;
* 	if the target is less than zero, then no element in the candidate array can add up to make target as zero. hence we return if target <0;
* 	if the length of path is k and target is achieved, we simply push the vector into the result. and return for other possibilites.
* 	for checking other possibilities, we need to remove our last element and iterate from the next number. since the length of the path vector is reduced, we increment k.
```
    void helper(vector<int> &v,vector<vector<int>>&res,vector<int>& path,int &k,int start,int target)
    {
        if(target <0)
        {
            return;
        }
        if(k==0 && target==0)
        {
            res.push_back(path);
            return;
        }
        for(int i=start;i<9;i++)
        {
            path.push_back(v[i]);
            helper(v,res,path,--k,i+1,target-v[i]);
            path.pop_back();
            k++;
        }
    }
};
```

