From the input string, we are trying to build a monotonically increasing result string.

If the input character is smaller than the back of the result string, we remove larger characters from the back **providing** there are more occurrences of that character in the input string.
```
string removeDuplicateLetters(string s, string res = "") {
  int cnt[26] = {}, used[26] = {};
  for (auto ch : s) ++cnt[ch - 'a'];
  for (auto ch : s) {
    --cnt[ch - 'a'];
    if (used[ch - 'a']++ > 0) continue;
    while (!res.empty() && res.back() > ch && cnt[res.back() - 'a'] > 0) {
      used[res.back() - 'a'] = 0;
      res.pop_back();
    }
    res.push_back(ch);
  }
  return res;
}
```
## Complexity Analysis
Runtime: O(n). We process each input character no more than 2 times.
Memory: O(1). We need the constant memory to track up to 26 unique letters.

