Idea is to have 2 arrays :
1. One to maintain the count of numbers of chars from a-z
2. Another to check whether a char is already "visited"

When parsing the given string, if we encounter a character that is already visited we simply continue.
If we visit a character that is not visited and if it is lesser than last character of the result string, and the count of the last character of the result string is > 0, we pop the last char of result and mark it as unvisited and repeat this step until the condition fails. Then we push the new character and continue;


```
class Solution {
public:
    string removeDuplicateLetters(string s) {

        if(s.length()==0 || s.length()==1)
            return s;

        int st[26] = {0};
        for(int i=0;i<s.size();i++)
        {
            st[s[i]-'a']++;
        }

        bool visited[26] = {false};

        string result = "*";
        for(int i=0;i<s.size();i++)
        {
            char c = s[i];
             --st[c-'a'];
            if(visited[c-'a']==true)
                continue;

            while(c < result.back() && st[result.back()-'a'])
            {
                visited[result.back()-'a'] = false;
                result.pop_back();
            }

            result+=c;
            visited[c-'a'] = true;
        }

        return result.substr(1);
    }
};
```

