solutions.content:
# Approach
We have to find a lexicographically smallest subsequence formed by deleting repeating characters in the original string such that every character stays only once. This means that the relative order of the characters need to be preserved.

We do this by - 
- First Create an array `lastIndex` which stores the last index of any character in the string `s`.
- Create a boolean array `seen` to keep track of whether we've seen a certain character or not.
- In our result string we have to pick characters which aren't already picked, also the current character picked should be `lexicographically greater` than the previous character. This can be achieved with the help of a stack . So create a stack `st`.
- Now, traverse over our string `s` and find our `curr`. `curr` repressents the index of the character in `alphabets`.
- If the character `curr` is already seen continue move on to next character.
- Else while the stack is not empty and our current character is smaller than the top of stack , pop the top of stack and mark it unseen , i.e `false`. This way our stack's any element is always greater than its previous.
- After this popping operation is done, the stack's top is less than our current character `s[i]` hence push `s[i]` in the stack and mark it `seen , i.e true`.
- At last, pop the stack elements and store it in a string `ans` and return `ans` in reverse order.

# I've explained the second test case below for better understanding.
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/668c7bd1-fcb1-4c1e-b584-6fb723b072b8_1695705396.801895.png)


# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    string removeDuplicateLetters(string s) {
        vector<int> lastIndex(26, 0);
        for (int i = 0; i < s.length(); i++){
            lastIndex[s[i] - 'a'] = i; 
        }

        vector<bool> seen(26, false); 
        stack<char> st;

        for (int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++) {
            int curr = s[i] - 'a';
            if (seen[curr]) continue; 
            while(st.size() > 0 && st.top() > s[i] && i < lastIndex[st.top() - 'a']){
                seen[st.top() - 'a'] = false; // pop out and mark unseen
                st.pop();
            }
            st.push(s[i]); 
            seen[curr] = true; 
        }

        string ans = "";
        while (st.size() > 0){
            ans += st.top();
            st.pop();
        }
        reverse(ans.begin(), ans.end());
        return ans;
    }
};
```
