solutions.content:
In order to get the result that is the smallest in lexicographical order among all possible results, **we can greedily pick the smallest characters for each postion**. To do so, we can always keep track of the **last occurrence postion** of each character in *s*, since **we can feel free to remove the duplicate before the last occurence postion** of it. 

Now we can use a data structure as Stack, while
**1. Stack is non-empty and
2. the character at current postion i, is smaller than the top of Stack and 
3. the character on the top of Stack can be seen in the future, which means we have not reached the last postion of it.**
Then we are free to do a Stack.pop() to update the beginning of the result. Same for the 2nd position, 3rd postion and so on.

Here is the clean Java code:
```
public String removeDuplicateLetters(String s) {
	int[] map = new int[26]; // To keep track of the last occurence of each character is the given string.
	char[] ch = s.toCharArray();
	for (int i=0; i<ch.length; i++) {
		map[ch[i] - 'a'] = i;
	}
	int[] counter = new int[26]; // we do need a "counter" to counte if we have put the character to the stack.
	Stack<Character> stack = new Stack<>();
	for (int i=0; i<ch.length; i++) {
		if (counter[ch[i] - 'a'] != 0) continue;
			// When meet those 3 conditions to update the top of stack:
			while (!stack.isEmpty() && ch[i] - stack.peek() < 0 && map[stack.peek() - 'a'] > i) {
				counter[stack.peek() - 'a'] = 0;
				stack.pop();
			}
			stack.push(ch[i]);
			counter[ch[i] - 'a'] = 1;
	}
	StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
	while (!stack.isEmpty()) sb.append(stack.pop());
	return sb.reverse().toString();
}
```

