# Approach
First count the frequecy of each characters.
Also use *isPresent* set to keep track of what characters are alrady included in answer.

Now iterate over given string and start constructing answer.
- If current character is present in answer then ignore it and check string further. Also reduce its frequency as its traversed.
- Otherwise compare this with last character of answer string. If its greater then current character then , remove it from answer if there are more occurence of that characters are yet to be traversed further in string. 
- Keep doing above step untill above condition is satisfied. 
- At last put current character in answer string, and mark it in *isPresent* and *freq*

**Note** : pop_back and push_back take O(1) time , because of this we can achive O(N) TC without using stack. Also use push_back insetad of '+' operator to append one character, cause '+' takses O(n) tiime.



# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(N)
- Space complexity:
O(N)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    string removeDuplicateLetters(string s) {
        unordered_map<char,int> freq;
        for(char c : s) {
            freq[c]++;
        }
        unordered_set<char> isPresent;
        string ans;
        for(char c : s) {
            if(isPresent.find(c)!=isPresent.end()) {
                freq[c]--;
                continue;
            }
            while(ans.size() > 0 && ans[ans.size() - 1] > c && freq[ans[ans.size() - 1]] > 0) {
                isPresent.erase(ans[ans.size() - 1]);
                ans.pop_back();

            }
            ans.push_back(c);
            freq[c]--;
            isPresent.insert(c);
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

