# Approach

First we will count the frequency for every element.Then we will declare a stack (which will be monotonic (increasing)).Now we will traverse through our given string and we will remove existing element of stack based on following two condition
i.) new element is lexiographically smaller then element present in stack.
ii.) element present in stack shoulb be removeable (it's frequency should be greater than 1).

Now we need to update our freq table accordingly..If we are popping a element from stack we should decrease it's freq because now we excluded it and  also when we are skipping element we should decrease the freq for future use.



# Complexity
- Time complexity:
0(n), where n is size of given string

- Space complexity:
0(1), as maximum no of element we can push in stack is 26.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    string removeDuplicateLetters(string s) {
        int n = s.size();
        vector<int> freq(26,0);
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            freq[s[i]-'a']++;
        }
        stack<char> st;
        vector<bool> check(26,false); 
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            char temp = s[i];
            if(check[temp-'a']){
                freq[temp-'a']--;
                continue;
            }
            while(!st.empty() && temp<st.top() && freq[st.top()-'a']>1){
                freq[st.top()-'a']--;
                check[st.top()-'a'] = false;
                st.pop();            
            }
            st.push(temp);
            check[temp-'a'] = true;
        }

        string ans;
        while(!st.empty()){
            ans.push_back(st.top());
            st.pop();
        }

        reverse(ans.begin(),ans.end());
        return ans;

    }
};
```

