# Brute Force Yucky solution
## Intuition
- Basically consider each letter from left to right, to be included or not in the result until you get to the last character of the input string. For each choice, you update your builder string

## Approach
- Start at index `i=0` and perform a recursive call based on these conditions:
```
- if charAt(i) was chosen already in previous recursion, skip.
    just recurse to i+1 without modifying anything
- if charAt(i) has a duplicate
Two choices:
    include the charAt(i) in the result, then recurse to i+1
    exclude the charAt(i) in the result, then recurse to i+1
- if charAt(i) has no duplicate
    no choice but to include it in result. then recurse to i+1
```
- Keep doing the above recursive calls until you get to a level of recursion where `i >= n`. When you reach this, update global result, with chosen characters in the string builder so far

## Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(2^n) - two possibilities every recursion: Either we choose the duplicate character and include in result, or we dont include it

- Space complexity:
O(n) recursion stack depth is at most O(n) I think.... and we need to store size n in a map

## Code
```
class Solution {
  String result = "";
  public String removeDuplicateLetters(String s) {
    result = s;
    int n = s.length();
    Map<Character, Integer> duplicates = new HashMap<>();
    Map<Character, Integer> count = new HashMap<>();
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
      char letter = s.charAt(i);
      count.put(letter, count.getOrDefault(letter, 0) + 1);
      if (count.get(letter) > 1)
        duplicates.put(letter, i);
    }

    if (duplicates.size() == 0)
      return s;

    Set<Character> chosen = new HashSet();
    recurse(s, new StringBuilder(), 0, chosen, duplicates);
    return result;
  }

  private void recurse(
    String s, 
    StringBuilder builder, 
    int i, 
    Set<Character> chosen, 
    Map<Character, Integer> duplicates
  ) {
    int n = s.length();
    if (i >= n) {
      String tmp = builder.toString();
      if (tmp.length() < result.length() || tmp.compareTo(result) < 0)
        result = tmp;
      return;
    }

    char letter = s.charAt(i);
    boolean isUnique = !duplicates.containsKey(letter);
    if (chosen.contains(letter)) {
      recurse(s, builder, i + 1, chosen, duplicates);
    } else if (isUnique) {
      builder.append(letter);
      chosen.add(letter);
      recurse(s, builder, i + 1, chosen, duplicates);
      pop(builder);
      chosen.remove(letter);
    } else { // duplicates.containsKey(letter)
      builder.append(letter);
      chosen.add(letter);
      recurse(s, builder, i + 1, chosen, duplicates);
      chosen.remove(letter);
      pop(builder);

      // check last index appearance of duplicate letter
      // can only skip this letter if there are remaining duplicates left
      int lastIndex = duplicates.get(letter);
      if (i < lastIndex)
        recurse(s, builder, i + 1, chosen, duplicates);
    }
  }

  private void pop(StringBuilder sb) {
    sb.deleteCharAt(sb.length() - 1);
  }
}
```

# Bootiful/Beautiful stack solution
## Intuition
- First figure out how to remove all duplicates. And then figure out how to tweak the algorithm so that you always consider lexicographically smaller characters. Use a stack to maintain a "smaller lexicographic ordering" by checking last element pushed to the stack and current iteration.

## Approach
- Create a mapping of letter to lastIndex
- Iterate input string from left to right. For every character `charAt(i)`, you have two possibilities
```
    Case 1: Character has no duplicates  - in which case you just need to add this to the result
    Case 2: Character has duplicates
```
- Case 2 is the tricky part
```
    For Case 2, either of the two things will happen:
      - result is empty/nothing is selected yet. Just add charAt(i) to result
                             previous
                                v
      - resultSoFar = [ . . . . .    ]
                                  ^
                                charAt(i)

        if previous is "smaller" than charAt(i), we just add charAt(i) to resultSoFar
          because we maintain lexicographic order
        if previous is "bigger" than charAt(i), we keep popping previous 
          (top of stack), until previous is "smaller" and insert charAt(i)
```
Theres a couple more checks for case 2 (making sure we dont run into empty stack exception, and its not the last occurrence of the previous - in other words, previous must be included and has no remaining duplicates on the right of i - this is what the "lastOccurence map" is used for).

## Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n) - iterate input string from left to right

- Space complexity:
O(n) - stack space

## Code
```
class Solution {
  public String removeDuplicateLetters(String s) {
    int n = s.length();
    Map<Character, Integer> lastOccurence = new HashMap<>(); 
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
      lastOccurence.put(s.charAt(i), i);
    Stack<Character> stack = new Stack<>();  
    Set<Character> seen = new HashSet<>();
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {  
      char letter = s.charAt(i); 
      if (seen.contains(letter)) 
        continue;

      // previous character in stack is "bigger" than current letter
      // and its not the last occurrence
      while (!stack.isEmpty()  
        && stack.peek().compareTo(letter) > 0      
        && lastOccurence.get(stack.peek()) > i) {  
        char removed = stack.pop();  // there are more occurences of previous letter, pop stack 
        seen.remove(removed);
      }

      stack.push(letter); 
      seen.add(letter); 
    }

    char[] result = new char[stack.size()];
    for (int i = stack.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--)
      result[i] = stack.pop();
    return new String(result);
  }
}

```

