# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Only put those characters in stack which form valid string.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
**Push in stack:**
- only those characters are pushed which are not already there in the stack using `visited` map.

**Pop from Stack**
1. stack is not empty which is obvious and,

2. the current character in string s is smaller than the top stack character, as we want to keep the smallest character at first,

*But what if the character we want to pop doesn't appear again?
point 3 is the answer.*

3. While popping we need to keep a check if the character does not appear again we will not pop it, using `lastIdx`.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    string removeDuplicateLetters(string s) {
        unordered_map<char, int> lastIdx;
        unordered_map<char, bool> visited;
        stack<char> st;
        string ans = "";
        for(int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++)
            lastIdx[s.at(i)] = i;


        for(int i = 0; i < s.size(); i++)
        {
            char ch = s.at(i);
            if(visited[ch]) continue;

            while(!st.empty() && ch < st.top() && i < lastIdx[st.top()])
            {
                visited[st.top()] = false;
                st.pop();
            }
            st.push(ch);
            visited[ch] = true;
        }

        while(!st.empty())
        {
            ans += st.top();
            st.pop();
        }
        reverse(ans.begin(), ans.end());
        return ans;
    }
};
```

